I assume that you already use [Jakarta XML Web Services][1] and [Jakarta XML Binding][2]. Your class annotated `jakarta.ws.WebService` turns Java objects into XML implicitly into your methods annotated `jakarta.ws.WebMethod` and returning instances of Java beans. You can simply pass those instances to [Jakarta JSON Binding][3]:

    import jakarta.ejb.Stateless;
    import jakarta.jws.WebMethod;
    import jakarta.jws.WebParam;
    import jakarta.jws.WebService;
    import jakarta.json.bind.Jsonb;
    import jakarta.json.bind.JsonbBuilder;
    
    @Stateless
    @WebService
    public class Manager {
    
        @WebMethod(operationName = &quot;getMyJavaBeanAsJson&quot;)
        public String getMyJavaBeanAsJson(@WebParam(name = &quot;id&quot;) final BigDecimal id) {
            final MyJavaBean myJavaBeanInstance = MyJavaBeanService.getInstance().find(id);
            try (final Jsonb jsonb = JsonbBuilder.create()) {
                return jsonb.toJson(myJavaBeanInstance);
            }
        }
    }

Please note that my answer uses only standard Jakarta EE (&gt;= 9) APIs with no third party dependencies.

Another solution consists in using Java Stax (Java API for XML Processing) to read the SOAP envelope, the SOAP body, the SOAP response, the SOAP return and then to turn only this part of the received XML into JSON. Either convert XML into a Java bean and use the solution above to turn in into JSON or turn the XML into JSON without using a Java bean. In my humble opinion, if you don&#39;t want to return the SOAP stuff in your JSON, use Stax to get only the SOAP return and pass it to `org.json.XML.toJSONObject(final String xml)` or any other tool able to convert XML to JSON.


